'''Sir John Logan Campbell''' (3 November 1817 – 22 June 1912) was a prominent New Zealand [[public figure]]. He was the son of Doctor John Campbell and his wife Catherine and grandson of the [[Campbell baronets#Campbell baronets, of Aberuchil (c. 1668)|3rd baronet]] of Aberuchil and [[Kilbryde Castle]], near [[Dunblane]], Perthshire. He was described by his contemporaries as "the father of [[Auckland]]".

== Early life==
[[File:John Logan Campbell, by Mungo Burton (1799-1882).jpg|thumb|150px|left|John Logan Campbell in the club dress of the Edinburgh Alleion Archers ([[Mungo Burton]], 1838)]]
John Logan Campbell was born in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland, on 3 November 1817. He had four sisters but his two elder brothers had died by the time he reached the age of 2, and he became the only surviving son.<ref>R C J Stone, ''Poenamo Revisited'', Godwit 2012 {{ISBN|978 1 86979 798 0}}</ref> Campbell graduated in medicine from the [[University of Edinburgh Medical School|University of Edinburgh]] in 1839<ref>''List of the graduates in medicine in the University of Edinburgh from MDCCV to MDCCCLXVI'', Edinburgh 1867</ref> and later that year sailed for the antipodes, [[New South Wales]], as a [[surgeon]] on the emigrant ship ''Palmyra''.<ref name="DNZB Campbell">{{DNZB|Stone|R. C. J.|1c3|Campbell, John Logan - Biography|31 March 2012}}</ref>

==Migration to New Zealand==
In 1840, he came to New Zealand, arriving first in [[Coromandel, New Zealand|Coromandel]] and thence to the capital of New Zealand, Auckland, which had been founded by [[Governor-General of New Zealand|Governor]] [[William Hobson]]. Campbell and [[William Brown (New Zealand politician)|William Brown]] (a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[lawyer]]) who arrived at the same time, were the first Europeans to settle in the area.

Campbell and Brown built the first house in Auckland (Acacia Cottage,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WM7735_Acacia_Cottage_Cornwall_Park_Auckland_New_Zealand|title=Acacia Cottage, Cornwall Park. Auckland. New Zealand. - Homesteads on Waymarking.com|website=Waymarking.com|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> which still survives), and opened the first shop. John Logan Campbell quickly became prominent in Auckland, both in business circles and in public life. He was a director of the [[Bank of New Zealand]], the [[New Zealand Loan and Mercantile Agency Company]], and the [[NZI|New Zealand Insurance Company]].<ref name="DNZB Campbell" />

==Auckland Province==
[[File:John Logan Campbell Statue, Greenlane.jpg|thumb|right|Statue of Sir John Logan Campbell at 308-312 Manukau Road, Epsom, placed at the twin formal entrances to his gift, [[Cornwall Park, Auckland]]]]
Campbell was appointed to the Auckland Executive Council on 20 March 1855, and he served until 15 September of that year.{{sfn|Scholefield |1950|p=181}} He was then [[Superintendent (New Zealand)|Superintendent]] of [[Auckland Province]] from 25 November 1855 to 17 September 1856.{{sfn|Scholefield |1950|p=179}}

==Member of Parliament==
