{{BLP sources|date=December 2012}} {{Infobox Governor | name = Mario López Valdez | image = Malova.png | office = [[Governor of Sinaloa]] | term_start = January 1, 2011 | term_end = December 31 2016 | predecessor = [[Jesús Aguilar Padilla]] | successor = [[Quirino Ordaz Coppel]] | birth_date = {{Birth date|1957|01|18}} | birth_place = [[Cubiri de la Loma]], [[Sinaloa]] | dead=alive | alma_mater = | party = [[National Action Party (Mexico)|National Action Party]] }}
'''Mario López Valdez''' (born January 18, 1957 in Cubiri de la Loma, Sinaloa), popularly known as Malova, is a Mexican businessman and politician, a member of the [[National Action Party (Mexico)|National Action Party]]. He was a senator of the state of [[Sinaloa]] from 2006 to 2010 and municipal president of [[Ahome Municipality]] from 2002 to 2004. He was the [[Governor of Sinaloa]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.portalangop.co.ao/motix/en_us/noticias/internacional/2011/10/47/Gov-drug-plagued-Mexico-state-send-kids-abroad,1ce59f9e-0edd-4c7e-8ce2-01f47fffe3d4.html|title=Gov. of drug-plagued Mexico state send kids abroad|date=November 25, 2011|work=Angola Press|accessdate=2 December 2012}}</ref> from 2011 to 2016.
==Background== Mario López Valdez is an accounting graduate of the Technological Institute of Los Mochis (ITLM). In 1984, he founded the MALOVA hardware store chain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ferretería MALOVA: Historia|url=http://www.malova.com.mx/pag/Historia.html|website=Ferretería MALOVA|accessdate=1 September 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150730223939/http://www.malova.com.mx/pag/Historia.html|archivedate=30 July 2015|df=}}</ref>
==Political career== In 2002, López Valdez was elected municipal president of [[Ahome Municipality]], whose capital is [[Los Mochis]]. In 2005 Governor [[Jesús Aguilar Padilla]] appointed him secretary of Planning and Development in the state government. He was elected in 2006 as the [[Institutional Revolutionary Party]] (PRI) candidate for the Mexican Senate, where he served on the Regional Development and the Environment, Natural Resources and Fisheries, and Agriculture and Water Resources commissions. On March 19, 2010, he resigned his membership of the PRI to run as candidate for governor of Sinaloa for the PAN. He was elected July 4, 2010, defeating PRI candidate [[Jesús Vizcarra Calderón]], a wealthy businessman and Culiacán municipal president who had been linked to local drug traffickers, including [[Ismael Zambada García|Ismael "El Mayo" Zambada]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilkinson|first1=Tracy|last2=Ellingwood|first2=Ken|title=Suspicions of drug ties don't hurt candidates|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/04/world/la-fg-mexico-narco-politics-20100703/2|accessdate=1 September 2014|work=The Los Angeles Times|date=4 July 2010}}</ref> He is also buddies with El Chapo.
As governor, López Valdez has been accused of corruption and links to organized crime.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Tim|title=On drug lord’s Mexican turf, lines blur among cops, pols, cartel|url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2014/02/27/219597/on-drug-lords-mexican-turf-lines.html#storylink=cpy|accessdate=1 September 2014|work=McClatchy DC News|date=27 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Valdez Cárdenas|first1=Javier|title=Los ataques al Noroeste, responsabilidad del gobernador: desplegado de accionistas|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2014/04/06/politica/005n1pol|accessdate=1 September 2014|work=La Jornada|date=6 April 2014}}</ref> In July 2014, he supported a bill that barred journalists from covering crime and public safety stories. However, López Valdez pledged to repeal the law just a few days after its unanimous passage in the state legislature, following a national outcry.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tucker|first1=Duncan|title=Mexican governor backtracks on state censorship after media outcry|url=http://latincorrespondent.com/media/mexican-governor-backtracks-state-censorship-media-outcry/|accessdate=1 September 2014|work=Latin Correspondent|date=8 August 2014}}</ref>
